segments.text: as good in the javelin as he was in the shot put and the discus.
I guess he was most consistent in the discus and was better, comparatively speaking, than the other athletes against whom he competed.
And he consistently won at Texas Relays, Kansas Relays, and Drake.
And he also placed very highly, I don't recall just how high, in the NCAA and AAU meet.
but George was a consistent point producer, a good friend, a good man.
He was also in Who's Who, American colleges and universities, a very good student, very popular on campus.
J.D.
Hampton, a distance man, class of 50, was another athlete that we admired.
J.D.
and George were co-captains, as I recall,
JD set the conference record in the mile.

He also ran the two mile and most of the time would win his event until we started running into the Midwestern schools and of course Kansas and Iowa and Iowa State and Oklahoma A&M they had always produced distance men and that was something that
other than J.D.
Hampton and Jerry Thompson at Texas, the Southwest Conference just didn't have distance men.
Now, in your era, basketball, G. Raleigh wasn't built yet, was it?
No, we played basketball in the little cracker box, the cozy little cracker box of DeWare Fieldhouse.
Describe an Aggie basketball game in those days.
Oh, it was loud, and the house was packed.
because what else were you going to do on a weekend or a weeknight at College Station if you didn't go to Guyon Hall and you didn't have a car?
You'd go to the basketball game, and besides, the upperclassmen would make sure that you would show up at the basketball game.
Were there any pranks or tricks that you all played on the enemy, like the Longhorns?
It didn't make any difference whether they were Longhorns or not.
It just made it sweeter if we could do it for the Longhorn.
But the stands in DeWare Field House were arranged in such a manner that they were right on the edge of the out-of-bounds line.
In fact, I think there was only three or four feet between the out-of-bounds line and where the concrete stands started.
And the upperclassmen would have, we freshmen,
sit on these concrete lips underneath the iron railing that went around.
And whenever the opposing team got the ball out of bounds, it was our job to try to kick the ball out of their hands while they were trying to inbounds it.
And the referees didn't care for that too much, and especially the opposing coach.
But Marty Corot, who was the coach then,
Marty didn't mind it at all.
Anything that we could do would have been a help.
Do you remember any special moments during an Aggie basketball game, one of a kind?
Well, it was always fun to watch Buddy Davis and John DeWitt work.
They were our two tall men.
Buddy, of course, was 6'10", 6'11".
DeWitt was about 6'4", 6'5".
DeWitt was also one of the most versatile athletes we ever had here.
John was all Southwest Conference in basketball, baseball, and he won the Southwest Conference 440 in track in 1952.
John was a class of 51, but he was taking a five-year architecture program, and he played his first three years of eligibility out in basketball and baseball
and then asked Colonel Andy if he could come out for track.
Colonel Andy had seen John run in intramurals before and had timed him in 50 flat.
And so Colonel Andy was just salivating to get John out there on the track.
And he did, and John proved his worth and won the conference 440 in 1952, which was his fifth year, but actually his first year of track eligibility.
And football.
Football.
Buddy Schaefer, I've already mentioned.
What about Bob Smith?
We had Bob Smith.
Bob and I had played football and run track against each other in high school.
He was class of 51.
And I'd never seen a better running back, a better slasher than Bob Smith.
And if he ever got past the line of scrimmage, it was all over.
He would really punish a linebacker, and a halfback didn't have a chance.
You'd have to hit him low, hit him around the ankles.
You couldn't tackle him.
You'd just have to hit him with a body block and hope you got him between you and the sidelines to knock him out of bounds.
And I saw him run for 285 yards against Kyle Roach and SMU.
in 1950 in the Cotton Bowl, and we beat them 25 to 20.
He set a new NCAA rushing record, 285 yards in that game.
We also had Glenn Lippman, who was in my class, class 52.
El Campo?
Yeah, from El Campo.
El Campo produced some fine athletes and fine students.
Glenn Lippman
Elo Noavitza, who was a guard, and Jero Natartus, who was an end.
All three were in the top ten academically.
Jero was valedictorian of our class.
And I don't recall exactly where Glenn and Elo placed, but they were in the top ten.
I'm grinning because all three of them obviously were of Irish ancestry.
Yeah.
Elo...
ELO was a Czech ancestry.
Glenn Lipman was German, possibly German-Jewish, I'm not sure.
And Gero was Greek.
And Glenn went on into mechanical engineering and went with some large engineering firm.
I don't recall which.
As far as you know, did most all of those athletic friends of yours
in their later lives, did they have the kind of achievement that you assumed they would?
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
They were tops in their field, and you called them boss five years after graduation.
Glenn was a supervisor of officials for the Southwest Conference in later years, and I would see him at all of our home football games.
here in the Letterman's Association, and his job was to evaluate the job that the officials did during the football games.
Jarrow was in the banking and savings and loan business, and I'm not clear about what Elo did.
I haven't seen Elo since, but I see Glenn frequently and Jarrow occasionally.
Now, I wrote down before we turned the machine on, athletic tales.
What are some of those?
Well, those are many and varied.
I'll start with Bones Irving first.
Bones was, shall we say, frugal.
And to give you an example,
After we got lights in Kyle Field, Bones would have the lights turned off in Kyle Field before the crowd got out of the stadium.
And they would have to make their way out of the stadium in the dark and find their cars in the dark because he wanted to save on electricity.
Bones drove a hard bargain when it came to getting not amenities, but what I would call necessities
out of the athletic director.
Even though Dog Dawson was the financial manager, Bones always had the last say.
And I remember Colonel Andy pleading with Bones to get a bus to take us on long trips, you know, a passenger type bus.
And Bones's first concession to that, that I recall in my sophomore year,
he let us take what we referred to as the Blue Goose, which was a long-stretched Chevrolet.
It was actually a Chevrolet sedan that had been cut in half and four or five seats put in it, and you could carry about 12 to 14 or 15 people.
We would have to take the Blue Goose from here to the Kansas Relays at Lawrence, Kansas.

We would start out early in the morning, Colonel Andy drove, he could barely see over the steering wheel, and he was a short guy, and we would drive to Dallas, have lunch at Wyatt's Cafeteria, and he would be there at the cash register to take up our chits, our checks as we came out, and he would examine each one carefully and look askance at you if the total went over more than
You'd get a lot of food for $3 in those days.
George Cadera and I were the budget busters.
I was always a chow hound, and of course Cadera weighed about 245.
He was a big guy.
And we would usually have the largest tickets.
We'd drive on up to Orange, Kansas the next day, compete in the preliminaries, finals on Saturday, drive back on Sunday.
We'd stay in a dormitory
on campus.
The following, two weeks after the Kansas relays, they would have the Drake relays in Des Moines, Iowa.
Ooh, long drive.
Well, we rebelled.
We told Colonel Andy that that is too far to be driving the Blue Goose.
That's three days, and you can't expect us to do that and run in a track meet.
And he allowed us out.
That was right, and he went to Bones to see what Bones could do about it.
He initially, I think, was going to try to go for a passenger bus, but even so, that would have been a brutal trip.
So he finally got with his friend Clyde Littlefield down in Texas, and he and Clyde Littlefield agreed to share a Pullman.
The Pullman would originate at Austin.
It would travel on Southern Pacific to Houston, where it would switch off to the Rock Island line,
We would jump in the Blue Goose and go over to North Zulich and you had to flag the train down at North Zulich.
But he had an agreement with the engineer, the conductor, that we would be out there and we would flag the train down at the water tower.
There was a water tower there and a very small railway station.
So we're all out there on the side of the railroad track with our baggage
And here comes the train, and Colonel Landy sees the train, and he goes out there in the middle of the track, and he's waving his arms back and forth so that the engineer could see him.
Well, the train is blowing its whistle and all this kind of stuff, and the train is getting closer and closer, and we're all worried because Colonel Landy is just waving harder and harder.
And he was jumping up and down.
Stop, USOB, stop.
Finally...
George Cadera and somebody else, they grabbed him and pulled him off of the track.
The train went right on by, but it stopped up at the water tower.
And that was where the engineer planned on stopping.
Coincidentally, it would place the Pullman where we were waiting for it at the tracks.
So, Colonel Andy's antics went for naught.
We'd get on the train and enjoy the Pullman trip up there.
We knew all the Texas guys.
We were all friends.
We were competitors, but friends nevertheless.
Now, in a meet like those two, about how many Aggie track team members went?
We would take a mile relay team.
That's four people.
The first year, my sophomore year that I went, we took three herders, Bob Hall, Bill Bless, and myself,
We took Jack Simpson, who was a pole vaulter, and George Cadera, who was a weight man.
Oh, and J.D.
Hampton and Julian Herring, because they had a good chance of placing in the distance events.
So 10 to 12.
10 to 12 guys, and we always did well at Drake Relays.
Now what did you, as you're going back and forth, what did you wear?
We wore...
We wore sport coats and slacks.
Didn't wear warm-ups?
No.
On the train?
No.
We were representing Texas A&M, and the Texas athletes dressed accordingly.
It was just an unwritten rule.
Did the Aggies and the Longhorn track team, did they sit near each other and talk?
Oh, yeah.
We had poker games, bridge games on the train.
As I say, we were friendly competitors.
What were either spoken or not spoken but clearly understood, what were Coach Andy's rules for y'all?
Colonel Andy's.
In regard to what?
When you were traveling.
What were you not to do and what were you to do when you were away from this campus?
Conduct ourselves like gentlemen.
We're representatives.
Texas A&M.
We take our books and make sure we study because when you go on a trip like that, you're gone for the better part of a week.
And take your books, study, help each other.
Just the way it was.
Did anybody do any smoking?
Yeah.
Jack Simpson would go out on the train platform.
Jack was a vet.
and of course he had smoked when he was in the service and he still had the habit and Bob Hall would be known to occasionally smoke.
Could anybody have a beer if they wanted to?
Did Colonel Andy have a policy about that on a trip?
Colonel Andy had no policies about smoking or drinking.
It was just understood

you're grown up now and uh if you smoke and drink it's your own detriment you're not hurting me okay colonel andy but there were no rules we i never knew of anybody dismissed from the track team for a quote violation of team rules we we didn't have any we policed ourselves the captains would take care of that coach didn't have to worry about it and you normally on those uh
to the relays, you stayed in a dorm.
When you went to the Southwest Conference meets, where did y'all stay?
In motels?
First of all, when we went to Kansas, we stayed in dorms.
When we went to Des Moines Island, we stayed in the Drake Hotel.
Oh, okay.
We went first class.
Okay.
And that surprised us, because we weren't used to that kind of thing.
What about in the...
When we went to the Southwest Conference meet,
We stayed in a motel.
I believe it was the South Congress Motel, or South Austin Motel on South Congress.
Let's see, other athletic tales.
Well, when we would go to Laredo, the first, my sophomore year, we took the Blue Goose.
you couldn't get away from that ubiquitous blue goose.
And we'd cram everybody in there and put the poles on top and the javelins on top and all this and lash them down.
And as we would go through South Texas, the upperclassmen had told we lower-classmen, now when we get down here to a certain spot in Falferius County,
Colonel Landy's going to tell you a story about a deer that he shot.
And so we got ready, and sure enough, we passed a certain spot in Thalferius County, and Colonel Landy would say, you see that live oak tree over there?

He says, I killed a buck over there, and I went over to see about him, and all of a sudden he jumped up and charged me, and I had my hunting knife, and we wrestled for ten minutes, and I finally cut his throat.
Going down to Lareda, he would point that out.
Coming back from Lareda, he would point that out.
For three years, I got that story.
And I don't know how many years he's been telling it.
Did you all go across the river?
We took the Blue Goose across the river.
And that was a mistake, because that Blue Goose was pretty long, and it had a long wheelbase.
And you just couldn't maneuver in some of those.
side streets down there.
And we went down to Boys Town just to see what it was like.
And we went to the Cadillac bar to have a queso dinner.
This is after the meet, of course.
And have one of those famous margaritas.
And Colonel Andy never went with us.
He stayed at the hotel.
My senior year, we chartered a regular passenger bus
and took the wives.
Those of us who could afford to, we'd have to pay for the wives' rooms.
And we would, all the boys would stay in their own room through the track team, and the wives would bunk up together down the hall in the hotel.
But things improved considerably.
I don't know where Bones found the money to do that,
whether he was getting a little more liberal in his dotage.
Now, of all of the athletic experiences you recall of your own, can you recall one or two that were among the most amusing, the goofiest, most ludicrous?
One other story about Cadera and Colonel Andy, and it had nothing to do with athletics.
It just occurred on an athletic trip.
We were going to Kansas for the Kansas Relays, and Cadera always carried his own shot and discus with him, and he put them in a duffel bag.
Colonel Andy told Cadera to put those things up on top of the blue goose.
Uh-oh.
I don't want those things down here in the passenger compartment.
Well, Cadera was afraid the shot would get away from him up there on the roof, and he would lose it.
So he sat on the back seat of the bus and stuffed that duffel bag underneath the back seat, put his feet on top of it, and we rode that way all the way up to Kansas.
About the time we started leaving Oklahoma,
started into Kansas.
An old farmer and his pickup truck pulled out from a side road and Colonel Andy had a jam on the brakes real hard.
Well that shot broke loose from that duffel bag and went up to the front of the Blue Goose and it hit the firewall right under Colonel Andy's feet.
He stopped the Blue Goose and
ran around to the back seat, and he had Cadera out of there by his ear.
And he said, Cadera, you blagging like SOB?
I told you to put that thing up.
You could have broken our legs.
And Cadera sheepishly sat in the back seat and held that shot put in his lap for the rest of the trip.
That's a good one.
That's a good one.
Other amusing ones that involve, any amusing ones that involved you?
Whether pranks or otherwise.
Well, I wasn't one given to playing pranks on our trips.
Well, if you want to call dropping water balloons out of the window at the Worthington Hotel in Fort Worth, pranks, yeah.
Who were y'all dropping them on?
We don't know.
Who ever happened to be down there?
Nobody got caught.
No, because right after we dropped them, we disappeared.
And all of your track efforts here, what were your proudest moments?
Well, I suppose one of my most proud moments was
when I won the low hurdles and the Drake relays in a snowstorm.
I just out mudded everybody else.
It wasn't that I was all that fast because truth be known if we were to line up for a 100 yard dash I'd probably come in last.
But I had strength and power and the mud and the slush didn't bother me and it bothered the shorter legged people a lot more.
I could go into overdrive a lot easier than they could.
and then gutting it out against Valjo Walker in the Southwest Conference meet here in 1951 when I ran faster than I ever thought I could, and so did Walker.
Now, what was your best time that you ever did?
In the highs, it was 14.2.
In the lows, it was 22.9.
All right, those are happy moments.
Any real disappointing moment?
Frustrating?
No.
I was, I was forking it.
Colonel Andy called me his money player.
He said if I was going to go to a horse race, I'd put my money on you because you ought to
You either win, place, or show.
And that was true.
I placed in every event that I ever entered.
Now, your worst injury was when you hurt your knee?
My worst injury occurred in the spring of my senior year at the Border Olympics at Laredo.
That was also an Olympic year.
I had my sights set on going to the Olympic tryout.
And I had a pretty good chance.
And I had trained hard in the off-season, and we had gone with the Sugar Bowl track meet, which meant that we had to train during the winter as well.
And I had won the highs at the Border Olympics, and we lined up for the lows, and we had a pretty impressive field there with Bobby Joe Ragsdale from A&M.
Billy Bless, Valjo Walker, Ralph Person from Texas.
All these guys were capable of breaking the conference record.
And several of us had and several of us did that year.
In fact, all of us did that year, just not in the conference meet necessarily.
And I was leading going over the fourth hurdle, which was unusual for me.
I would usually make up the ground in the latter part of the race when the short legged guys were trying to stretch it to the next hurdle.
Now I was leading over the fourth hurdle and I kicked out my right leg first to go over the hurdle and something snapped right behind and just above my knee.
That quadriceps muscle had, or the

lower part of the gluteus maximus had come loose and I felt like I'd been shot and I was in the middle lane everybody of course went past me and nothing flat and I hobbled on one leg over to the grass and pitched out and grabbed my leg and started moaning and groaning and I was out for two months it was two months before I could get back in action
And of course, that put me two months behind everybody else.
And I got back in some semblance of shape and was able to run.
By the time we went out to a four-way meet at the Los Angeles Coliseum with Southern Cal, UCLA, and Texas, we drove to Fort Worth, got on a DC-7, and flew out to Los Angeles.
and gave a good account of ourselves out there.
We finished, barely finished second to USC.

I think we would have won the meet, but one of our regular mile relay guys stepped in a hole on the infield where they have the water faucets to turn on the, and he stepped in the hole and sprained his ankle, and we had to use
a substitute guy on the mile relay, and just barely got beaten in the mile relay.
Otherwise, we would have won that meet.
But I got back in some semblance of shape.
I ran second to Jack.
His last name escapes me now.
But he was the previous year's NCAA champion.
And later that year set a new world record, 13.5.
So I stayed within sight of him, but that was about it.
Then in the Southwest Conference meet, Valjo Walker won that.
Willie Valls from Texas was second.
And I was about a foot behind Willie.
And I ran 14.3.
which surprised me.
And of course I was out of the running as far as going to the Olympic trials was concerned due to losing that two months.
Now y'all didn't have, during your years, were no tragedies that you and your buddies had to cope with?
Nobody broke a leg, nobody got killed, nobody had a bad car wreck?
No.
Minor stuff.
Yeah.
Let's see, you mentioned tutoring.
Describe that.
Our freshman class, we had a good group of students, and we had some students who didn't do as well as others.
Put it that way.
And the midterm grades came out in about the second or third week of January.
And then we took a midterm break, come back to register for the spring on the 30th of January.
When I got back from spring, we didn't call it spring break then.
I don't recall what we called it.
Easter.
No, it wasn't Easter.
This was the 30th of January.
Oh, semester.
We used to call it semester break.
When I got back from that, Dog Dawson,
came up to the dorm one evening and said, I need to talk to you.
Sure, Doc.
He said, some of our guys
